text.tspan: DataLad is a general purpose tool for managing everything involved in
digital data workflow – regardless of data types, content, size, location,
generation, or volatility. It provides functionality to share, retrieve, and
version control data in a distributed fashion, and it aids managing the
evolution of digital objects in a way that elevates their FAIRness.
"DataLad - An Introduction" comprises key parts of the DataLad
Handbook project (handbook.datalad.org), and combines them into an
overview of the tool and its basic features. Following the "Basics" part of
the online handbook, it combines hands-on, code-along tutorials with
accessible explanations of technical concepts and workflows. You are invited
to fire up your computer's terminal and follow along, but you do not need
to be a programmer, computer scientist, or Linux crack. If you have never
touched your computer’s shell before, you will be fine. No prior knowledge
about Git or git-annex is required. This book will teach you simple, yet
advanced principles of data management for reproducible, comprehensible,
transparent, and FAIR data projects. It does so with hands-on tool use of
DataLad and its underlying software, blended with clear explanations of
relevant theoretical backgrounds whenever necessary, and by demonstrating
organizational and procedural guidelines and standards for data related
projects on concrete examples.
This introduction is for you if you are interested in learning how to use
DataLad. Regardless of your background and personal use cases for the
tool, this introduction will teach you the principles of DataLad, by applying
them to real-world challenges.
